{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Agarwal (2020) and Cummings et al. (2019) show there exist data distributions on which enforcing fairness for a private algorithm would necessarily result in trivial accuracy.",
    "Feldman (2020) and Sanyal et al. (2022) further study this tension under the assumption that the data has a long-tailed structure.",
    "Their work suggests that, for a nontrivial target accuracy, one has to trade off between privacy and fairness.",
    "Sanyal et al. (2022) validate the theory on several real-world data sets and show that relaxing the target overall accuracy is an effective method to improve fairness.",
    "In addition to developing better algorithms, it is crucial to understand the fundamental limits arising from imposing DP constraints."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Agarwal (2020) and Cummings et al. (2019) show there exist data distributions on which enforcing fairness for a private algorithm would necessarily result in trivial accuracy.",
    "Feldman (2020) and Sanyal et al. (2022) further study this tension under the assumption that the data has a long-tailed structure.",
    "Sanyal et al. (2022) validate the theory on several real-world data sets and show that relaxing the target overall accuracy is an effective method to improve fairness."
  ]
